As mention in our documentation of [Configuring team settings|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jiraportfolioserver0225/configuring-team-settings-967341596.html] under Configuring team velocity > Forecasted velocity:
{quote}
The team velocity that's forecasted for the next few sprints, based on:
* the team's performance over past sprints
* the availability of your team members
{quote}

Above statement are too general and do not explain how Forecasted Velocity are calculated. Please update the documentation to include some example on how Forecasted Velocity are calculated. Below are the example from developer:
{quote}
By default, the `Forecasted Velocity` is the number of story points in the `Team velocity` field. When there are team members, the algorithm will divide those story points over all the team members (including virtual users) equally. When one or more team members (including virtual users) are not available for (part of) the sprint, it will take that into account.

For example, let's say there are 30 story points in the `Team velocity` field. The `Forecasted Velocity` will, by default, be 30 story points. When there are 2 team members, the `Forecasted Velocity` will still be 30 story points: 15 story points for each team member. When 1 team member is only available for half of the sprint, the `Forecasted Velocity` will be 22.5 story points: 15 story points for the team member that is available for the whole sprint and 7.5 story points for the team member that is only available for half of the sprint.
{quote}

h3. Problem Definition:
Currently when an issue is excluded from a plan you can edit the issue sources under the plan settings *"Configure >> Issue Sources >> Edit Issue Sources" * then the items that were excluded will show up unselected, and you can manually review these items to get a list of issues or releases excluded from a plan this way and you can re-add those items to to the plan by reselecting them and submitting the changes.

However, there are no other ways to generate a list of issues or releases excluded from a plan.  If an issue or release is accidentally excluded there is no easy way to identify the item other than the method outlined above

h3. Suggested Solution
Provide a report in portfolio with a list of issues OR a JQL search option such as:
{code}
issue IN plan()
issue NOT IN plan()
issue Excluded from plan()
fixVersion IN plan()
fixVersion NOT IN plan()
fixVersion Excluded from plan()
{code}
Any option to generate a full list of items that are expressly excluded from a plan for easy identification

h3.Workaround
To look up version exclusions in the DB:
{code}
SELECT * FROM "AO_D9132D_EXCLUDED_VERSIONS";
{code}

Excluded issues are saved in the "entity_property" table noting the entity_id aligns with the issue id on the jiraissue table:
{code}
SELECT * FROM entity_property WHERE ENTITY_NAME='IssueProperty' AND PROPERTY_KEY='jpo-exclude-from-plan'; 
{code}

h3. Expected Behavior
Warn users that are looking to share their Portfolio plan via the 'embed' link that they need to disable clickjacking protection.

h3. Actual Behavior
This is not documented and, when using an 'embed' element from Jira in any page it will not load.

In the browser's console you should find a message similar to the following:

{noformat:borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
Refused to display 'http://jira.mycompany.com/secure/PortfolioReportView.jspa' in a frame because an ancestor violates the following Content Security Policy directive: "frame-ancestors 'self'".
{noformat}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
The following steps apply to embedding a Portfolio roadmap on a Confluence page. However, this should be true for any HTML page supporting 'embed' elements.
# Within any Portfolio plan *using the New Planning Experience*, click "Share" near the top-right corner;
# Toggle the switch for "Embed URL";
# Copy the element;
# Create a Confluence page;
# Add a [HTML Macro|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/html-macro-38273085.html] and paste the copied element into it;
# Save the page;

Note that the element will not be displayed.

h3. Workaround
As indicated in [Security headers in Jira|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirakb/security-headers-in-jira-939919914.html], add the following parameter to Jira's [startup options|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/setting-properties-and-options-on-startup-938847831.html] and restart it.

{noformat:borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
-Dcom.atlassian.jira.clickjacking.protection.exclude=/secure/PortfolioReportView.jspa
{noformat}
